descript.abstract: The Geothermal Information Layer for Oregon, Release 2 (GTILO-Release 2) is the Oregon Department of Geology and Mineral Industries' (DOGAMI) geospatial database system that stores and manages Oregon's geothermal resource information. Two geospatial databases were assembled for this release: the Geothermalwell database and the Geothermalspring database. The Geothermalspring_database holds 690 points representing springs that are produced by the emergence of geothermally heated groundwater in Oregon.
descript.purpose: This Geothermal spring geospatial file was developed to illustrate those areas in Oregon that either have been investigated for geothermal resource potential or show potential for a geothermal resource.
descript.supplinf:
GTILO-Release 2 is a two-part spatial database: Geothermalspring_database and Geothermalwell_database.
Revisions and updates to this layer: 34 new thermal springs.
Understand that there is no universally accepted definition of a hot and warm spring. The term "hot" or "warm" in the spring's name has also led to the listing of some springs.

procstep.procdesc: The AllStates 20091001.zip file was downloaded from the U.S. Geological Survey's Geographic Names Information system's (GNIS) Website. The zip file was expanded and the GNIS database was quered to search for all records related to springs in Oregon. This query was then filtered to return only the names for hot and warm springs.

procstep.procdesc: A Microsoft Excel spreadsheet of the GNIS query of hot and warm springs was imported into ArcMap and converted into point features. Then a comparison was made between the point features and the points in GTILO-Release 1's hot and warm springs layer, specifically looking for non-matched points. This audit-like comparison revealed that approximately 34 GNIS records were missed or otherwise overlooked and not incorporated into the earlier version of GTILO-Release 1. These records were copied and pasted into GTILO for this release.

attracc.attraccr: The accuracy of this data is dependent on (1) detail level (e.g. location information) of the source material and (2) interpretation procedures for capturing that source. Field checking of the data was not performed.

dataqual.logic: No duplicate features exist. Point data are represented by a single set of coordinate pairs. Because the data are from multiple sources, terminology varies and similar characteristics may be described differently.
dataqual.complete:
Spatial data are presented in the form of points representing natural thermal springs and the coverage is statewide. All spring attributes were captured from their reference source. All fields are attributed.
A characteristic of thermal springs in Oregon is that they usually represent a group of affiliated springs. In previous studies, it was customary to count each spring group but not every spring in that group. Thus, the number of thermal springs in the Hot and Warm Springs coverage is not a definite figure. In other words, a detailed on-the-ground and historical analysis of a single site may result in a revision of the number of thermal springs. Examples of thermal springs that constitute "one" group of hot springs are: Borax Springs, Mickey Springs, and Alvord Springs. The University of Idaho counted each spring in the three spring groups mentioned above. For this compilation, we did the same but only when a spring, which would have been otherwise included in a group, was separately shown on a U.S. Geological Survey 1:24,000-scale quadrangle map.

horizpa.horizpar: The method of digitization of thermal spring locations involved heads-up digitization from U.S. Geological Survey Digital Raster (DRG) Image of 1:24,000-scale quadrangles on the computer screen by using a computer mouse to scribe the feature. The DRG also acted as a marked base to guide and adjust the position of a previously scribed thermal spring feature based on thermal springs depicted on the DRG. The accuracy of this data depends on a number of different types of errors: geodetic, machine, cartographic, and random errors. Not least of which depends on the level of detail of the source material and the interpretation procedures for capturing that source.
